SIMPLE: pulpit
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pulpit
<hw>Pul"pit</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>pulpitum</ets>: cf. OF. <ets>pulpite</ets>, F.
<ets>pulpitre</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>An elevated place, or inclosed stage, in a church,
in which the clergyman stands while preaching.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I stand like a clerk in my <qex>pulpit</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The whole body of the clergy; preachers as a class;
also, preaching.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I say the <qex>pulpit</qex> (in the sober use⟦br⟧
Of its legitimate, peculiar powers)⟦br⟧
Must stand acknowledged, while the world shall stand,⟦br⟧
The most important and effectual guard,⟦br⟧
Support, and ornament of virtue's cause.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A desk, or platform, for an orator or public
speaker.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- 4. (Fig.) An office or condition of public prominence in which a
person can gain wide public attention, thereby permitting him to exhort
the public on moral or political matters. "The presidency is a bully
pulpit." -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pulpit</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pulpit
<hw>Pul"pit</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the pulpit, or
preaching; <as>as, a <ex>pulpit</ex> orator; <ex>pulpit</ex>
eloquence.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pulpited</ent>⟦br⟧
